stylometry: @Risk is used to run simulation models.  @RISK explores possible solutions and returns a distribution of outputs, not just a single bottom line answer.  This is one of the advantages of @RISK over regular solver programs.  We use information from the spreadsheet with the function "RISKSIMTABLE" to input values into our model for an uncertain variable.  When we run simulations with five inputs, (and 1000 iterations), 1000 explorations are done for each simulation.  The data is returned as a distribution, and tells us the minimum, maximum, mean, and standard deviation for each simulation.  When picking the optimal solution, we look for one that has a minimum, maximum, and mean that we deem acceptable (high or low, depending on what whether we are trying to minimize costs or maximize revenues, for example) and also has a low standard deviation to ensure that the solution is relatively reliable.
